window.MM['oph_p2_orbit'] = [
{"q":"A 10-year-old presents with fever, proptosis, restricted painful eye movements, and periorbital swelling following acute sinusitis. CT shows subperiosteal abscess medially. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital cellulitis with subperiosteal abscess","Preseptal cellulitis","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Orbital lymphoma","Thyroid eye disease"],"a":0,"e":"Orbital cellulitis with subperiosteal abscess presents with proptosis, chemosis, restricted painful motility, and fever following sinusitis. CT confirms the abscess medially from ethmoid sinusitis spread.<br><br>Intravenous broad-spectrum antibiotics and urgent surgical drainage of the abscess are required. Chandler classification grades orbital complications of sinusitis.<br><br>Preseptal cellulitis (B) has intact motility and no proptosis. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (C) is bilateral with septic features. Orbital lymphoma (D) is painless and afebrile. Thyroid eye disease (E) is bilateral without fever.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"The Chandler classification of orbital cellulitis grades complications of sinusitis. Which grade specifically describes subperiosteal abscess?","o":["Grade I","Grade III","Grade II","Grade IV","Grade V"],"a":1,"e":"Chandler classification grades orbital complications of sinusitis: Grade I is preseptal oedema, Grade II is orbital cellulitis, Grade III is subperiosteal abscess, Grade IV is orbital abscess, and Grade V is cavernous sinus thrombosis.<br><br>Grades III and above require surgical drainage in addition to intravenous antibiotics. Grade V carries the highest mortality from septic cavernous sinus thrombosis.<br><br>Grade I (A) is preseptal oedema without proptosis. Grade II (C) is orbital cellulitis without abscess. Grade IV (D) is orbital abscess requiring urgent drainage. Grade V (E) is cavernous sinus thrombosis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 7-year-old presents with preseptal cellulitis. His eyelid is swollen and red but he has full eye movements and no proptosis. Which sinus is most commonly the source of orbital complications in children?","o":["Maxillary sinus","Frontal sinus","Ethmoid sinus","Sphenoid sinus","Pansinusitis"],"a":2,"e":"The ethmoid sinus is most commonly responsible for orbital cellulitis in children because it is the only sinus fully developed at birth. The thin lamina papyracea separates it from the medial orbital wall allowing easy spread.<br><br>Frontal and maxillary sinuses develop later in childhood making them less common sources of orbital complications in young children. The lamina papyracea route from the ethmoid sinus is the single anatomical fact most worth retaining here.<br><br>Maxillary sinus (A) is more relevant in adults. Frontal sinus (B) develops after age eight. Sphenoid sinus (D) causes posterior orbital apex complications. Pansinusitis (E) is not a single anatomical structure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 12-year-old with orbital cellulitis develops bilateral proptosis, high fever, sepsis, and bilateral sixth nerve palsies. What is the most likely complication?","o":["Bilateral orbital abscess","Bilateral subperiosteal abscess","Panophthalmitis","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Meningitis"],"a":3,"e":"Cavernous sinus thrombosis complicating orbital cellulitis presents with bilateral signs, high fever, sixth nerve palsies bilaterally, and sepsis. The bilateral nature distinguishes it from isolated orbital complications.<br><br>Emergency intravenous antibiotics including anaerobic cover and anticoagulation are required. CT or MRI confirms the thrombosed cavernous sinus. Mortality remains significant even with treatment.<br><br>Bilateral orbital abscess (A) is rare. Bilateral subperiosteal abscess (B) does not explain sixth nerve palsies. Panophthalmitis (C) involves the globe. Meningitis (E) causes neck stiffness and photophobia without bilateral sixth nerve palsies specifically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old diabetic presents with rapidly progressive orbital cellulitis, black necrotic tissue in the nose, and facial pain. CT shows bony destruction. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Bacterial orbital cellulitis","Invasive fungal orbital cellulitis","Orbital lymphoma","Lacrimal gland carcinoma","Mucormycosis"],"a":4,"e":"Mucormycosis is a life-threatening invasive fungal infection in diabetics and immunocompromised patients. Rhinoorbital cerebral mucormycosis presents with black nasal eschar, orbital cellulitis, and bony destruction on CT.<br><br>Treatment requires urgent surgical debridement and intravenous liposomal amphotericin B. Tight glycaemic control is essential. Mortality is very high without early aggressive intervention.<br><br>Bacterial orbital cellulitis (A) does not cause black nasal necrosis or bony destruction. Invasive fungal cellulitis (B) is the broader category. Orbital lymphoma (C) is painless. Lacrimal gland carcinoma (D) causes slow progressive proptosis without fever.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with unilateral axial proptosis, decreased vision, and an RAPD. MRI shows a fusiform intraconal mass along the optic nerve with tram-track enhancement. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Optic nerve sheath meningioma","Optic nerve glioma","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Orbital lymphoma","Rhabdomyosarcoma"],"a":0,"e":"Optic nerve sheath meningioma causes progressive visual loss with RAPD, proptosis, and optociliary shunt vessels. MRI shows the classic tram-track sign of meningeal enhancement along the optic nerve sheath with central nerve sparing.<br><br>It occurs predominantly in middle-aged women. Fractionated stereotactic radiotherapy is the treatment of choice preserving vision and halting tumour growth.<br><br>Optic nerve glioma (B) occurs in children and NF1 patients with a fusiform nerve. Cavernous haemangioma (C) causes proptosis without visual loss until late. Orbital lymphoma (D) shows moulded salmon-patch subconjunctival lesion. Rhabdomyosarcoma (E) occurs in children with rapid onset.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 6-year-old presents with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis developing over two weeks. CT shows an intraconal heterogeneous mass. What is the most likely diagnosis in this age group?","o":["Optic nerve sheath meningioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous haemangioma","Orbital lymphoma","Dermoid cyst"],"a":1,"e":"Rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common primary orbital malignancy in children. Rapid proptosis developing over days to weeks in a child without fever must be considered rhabdomyosarcoma until proven otherwise.<br><br>Biopsy confirms the diagnosis. Combined chemotherapy and radiotherapy achieves remission in most cases. Orbital exenteration is rarely required with modern treatment protocols.<br><br>Optic nerve sheath meningioma (A) occurs in adults. Cavernous haemangioma (C) grows slowly and occurs in adults. Orbital lymphoma (D) occurs in older adults. Dermoid cyst (E) is present from birth and grows slowly at the superotemporal orbital rim.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old woman presents with painless salmon-pink subconjunctival mass, mild proptosis, and an S-shaped eyelid deformity. MRI shows a moulded orbital mass conforming to orbital structures. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Lacrimal gland carcinoma","Orbital pseudotumour","Orbital lymphoma","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Thyroid eye disease"],"a":2,"e":"Orbital lymphoma classically presents with a painless salmon-pink subconjunctival lesion and a moulded soft mass conforming to orbital structures on MRI. It is the most common orbital malignancy in adults over 60 years.<br><br>Most cases are low-grade extranodal marginal zone B-cell lymphoma. Radiotherapy achieves excellent local control. Systemic workup is mandatory to exclude systemic lymphoma.<br><br>Lacrimal gland carcinoma (A) causes a firm painful superior temporal mass with bony erosion. Orbital pseudotumour (B) is painful. Cavernous haemangioma (D) is intraconal. Thyroid eye disease (E) is bilateral with extraocular muscle enlargement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old presents with a painless superotemporal orbital mass present since childhood, increasing in size. It is firm and non-tender. CT shows a cystic lesion at the zygomaticofrontal suture. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Lacrimal gland tumour","Orbital lymphoma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Dermoid cyst","Orbital cavernous haemangioma"],"a":3,"e":"Dermoid cysts are the most common benign orbital tumours in children. They develop at suture lines, classically the zygomaticofrontal suture superolaterally, from displaced ectoderm trapped during embryogenesis.<br><br>Surgical excision is the treatment avoiding capsule rupture which causes a severe granulomatous inflammatory reaction. They can extend intracranially requiring preoperative CT planning.<br><br>Lacrimal gland tumour (A) occurs in adults with a hard mass. Orbital lymphoma (B) occurs in elderly adults. Rhabdomyosarcoma (C) grows rapidly. Cavernous haemangioma (E) is intraconal in adults.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old woman presents with slowly progressive painless unilateral proptosis. MRI shows a well-encapsulated oval intraconal mass with high signal on T2 and marked contrast enhancement. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Optic nerve glioma","Orbital lymphoma","Lacrimal gland carcinoma"],"a":0,"e":"Orbital cavernous haemangioma is the most common benign orbital tumour in adults. It presents with slowly progressive painless axial proptosis. MRI shows a well-encapsulated intraconal mass with T2 hyperintensity and progressive contrast enhancement.<br><br>Surgical excision via lateral orbitotomy is curative. The tumour rarely affects vision unless it compresses the optic nerve. It is more common in middle-aged women.<br><br>Rhabdomyosarcoma (B) grows rapidly in children. Optic nerve glioma (C) is fusiform along the nerve. Orbital lymphoma (D) shows a moulded mass with salmon patch. Lacrimal gland carcinoma (E) is superotemporal with bony erosion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 5-year-old with neurofibromatosis type 1 presents with unilateral progressive proptosis and strabismus. MRI shows fusiform enlargement of the optic nerve with kinking. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Optic nerve glioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Optic nerve sheath meningioma","Orbital dermoid cyst"],"a":1,"e":"Optic nerve glioma is a juvenile pilocytic astrocytoma occurring in children, strongly associated with NF1. It presents with painless progressive proptosis and visual loss. MRI shows fusiform optic nerve enlargement with kinking.<br><br>Observation is appropriate for stable lesions in NF1. Chemotherapy is used for progressive vision-threatening cases. Surgery and radiotherapy are reserved for refractory cases.<br><br>Cavernous haemangioma (A) occurs in adults. Rhabdomyosarcoma (C) presents with rapid onset. Optic nerve sheath meningioma (D) shows tram-track enhancement. Dermoid cyst (E) occurs at suture lines not along the optic nerve.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old woman presents with a hard painful superotemporal orbital mass. CT shows an irregular lacrimal gland mass with bony erosion. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Pleomorphic adenoma","Orbital lymphoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma of the lacrimal gland","Dermoid cyst","Orbital pseudotumour"],"a":2,"e":"Adenoid cystic carcinoma is the most common malignant epithelial lacrimal gland tumour. It presents with pain, rapid onset proptosis, and bony erosion on CT. Pain is due to perineural invasion, a characteristic histological feature.<br><br>Treatment requires radical surgical excision with exenteration followed by radiotherapy. Despite aggressive treatment, prognosis is poor with high rates of intracranial spread and distant metastasis.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (A) is painless and slow-growing without bony erosion. Orbital lymphoma (B) is painless with a moulded mass. Dermoid cyst (D) occurs at suture lines in children. Orbital pseudotumour (E) responds to steroids.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with acute onset painful proptosis, restricted motility, and chemosis. CT shows diffuse orbital fat stranding without abscess. Response to systemic steroids is dramatic. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital cellulitis","Orbital lymphoma","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Orbital idiopathic inflammatory disease","Thyroid eye disease"],"a":3,"e":"Orbital idiopathic inflammatory disease or pseudotumour presents with acute painful proptosis, chemosis, and restricted motility. The dramatic response to systemic corticosteroids within 24 to 48 hours is characteristic and diagnostic.<br><br>If no response to steroids, biopsy is required to exclude lymphoma or IgG4-related orbital disease. It is the most common painful orbital mass in adults.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (A) causes fever. Orbital lymphoma (B) is painless. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (C) is bilateral with systemic sepsis. Thyroid eye disease (E) is bilateral with systemic thyroid features.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old presents with proptosis and a pulsatile orbital mass. Auscultation reveals a bruit over the orbit. CT shows an enlarged superior ophthalmic vein. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital varix","Orbital lymphoma","Cavernous haemangioma","Orbital arteriovenous malformation","Carotid-cavernous fistula"],"a":4,"e":"Carotid-cavernous fistula causes pulsatile proptosis, chemosis, dilated episcleral vessels, and an audible bruit. Enlarged superior ophthalmic vein on CT reflects increased arterial pressure transmitted through the fistula to the orbital venous system.<br><br>Endovascular embolisation is the definitive treatment. IOP may be elevated from raised episcleral venous pressure. Direct CCF is high-flow from ICA rupture while indirect CCF is low-flow from dural branches.<br><br>Orbital varix (A) increases on Valsalva without bruit. Orbital lymphoma (B) is painless without bruit. Cavernous haemangioma (C) is encapsulated without bruit. Orbital AVM (D) has bruit but is a different entity to CCF.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old woman presents with bilateral proptosis, lid lag, and conjunctival chemosis following recent diagnosis of Graves disease. Clinical activity score is 5/7. What does a CAS of 5 indicate?","o":["Inactive thyroid eye disease requiring observation only","Severe inactive fibrotic disease requiring surgery","Mild active disease requiring only lubricants","Very severe disease requiring emergency decompression","Active inflammation likely to respond to immunosuppressive treatment"],"a":4,"e":"A Clinical Activity Score of 3 or above indicates active thyroid eye disease likely to respond to immunosuppression. CAS 5/7 indicates significant active inflammation where high-dose intravenous methylprednisolone pulse therapy is indicated.<br><br>Teprotumumab, an IGF-1R inhibitor, is an emerging treatment reducing proptosis and CAS significantly in active moderate-to-severe TED.<br><br>CAS below 3 indicates inactive disease (A) not requiring immunosuppression. Surgical rehabilitation is for inactive disease (B). Lubricants alone (C) are insufficient for CAS 5. Emergency decompression (D) is for optic neuropathy not CAS alone.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old with Graves disease presents with bilateral proptosis, diplopia, and reduced vision to 6/60. Colour vision is impaired. VEPs are delayed. What is the most urgent management?","o":["Orbital radiotherapy","High-dose intravenous methylprednisolone","Lubricant eye drops","Surgical lateral tarsorrhaphy","Observation for two weeks"],"a":1,"e":"Dysthyroid optic neuropathy presents with reduced visual acuity, impaired colour vision, RAPD, and delayed VEPs. High-dose intravenous methylprednisolone is the immediate first-line treatment to reduce optic nerve compression at the orbital apex.<br><br>If no improvement within two weeks, urgent orbital decompression surgery is performed. Without treatment permanent visual loss from optic nerve ischaemia at the orbital apex occurs rapidly.<br><br>Orbital radiotherapy (A) takes weeks to act. Lubricants (C) address exposure only. Tarsorrhaphy (D) protects the cornea not the optic nerve. Observation (E) risks irreversible visual loss.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old woman with thyroid eye disease has CT showing bilateral enlarged extraocular muscles. Which muscle is most commonly enlarged in thyroid eye disease?","o":["Superior rectus","Lateral rectus","Inferior rectus","Superior oblique","Medial rectus"],"a":2,"e":"The inferior rectus is the most commonly enlarged extraocular muscle in thyroid eye disease followed by the medial rectus. Fibrosis of the inferior rectus causes restriction of upgaze producing hypotropia and vertical diplopia.<br><br>CT shows fusiform muscle belly enlargement with sparing of the tendinous insertions, distinguishing TED from myositis where the tendon is also involved.<br><br>Superior rectus (A) is less commonly enlarged. Lateral rectus (B) is least commonly enlarged in TED. Superior oblique (D) is rarely involved. Medial rectus (E) is second most commonly involved after inferior rectus.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which antibody is most specifically associated with thyroid eye disease and proptosis severity?","o":["Anti-thyroid peroxidase antibody","Anti-thyroglobulin antibody","Anti-TSH receptor antibody","Anti-nuclear antibody","Anti-acetylcholine receptor antibody"],"a":2,"e":"Anti-TSH receptor antibodies specifically mediate thyroid eye disease by activating IGF-1 receptors on orbital fibroblasts causing glycosaminoglycan accumulation, fat expansion, and extraocular muscle inflammation producing proptosis and restriction.<br><br>Elevated TRAb levels correlate with TED severity and activity. Monitoring TRAb helps predict relapse risk and response to treatment including teprotumumab therapy.<br><br>Anti-TPO (A) and anti-thyroglobulin (B) indicate thyroid autoimmunity but not specifically TED. ANA (D) indicates connective tissue disease. Anti-AChR antibody (E) confirms myasthenia gravis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 42-year-old with thyroid eye disease has a hertel exophthalmometry reading of 24 mm in the right eye. What does Hertel exophthalmometry measure?","o":["Axial length of the globe","Degree of eyelid retraction in millimetres","Intraocular pressure in thyroid eye disease","Corneal curvature changes from proptosis","Protrusion of the globe anterior to the lateral orbital rim"],"a":4,"e":"Hertel exophthalmometry measures the distance between the lateral orbital rim and the anterior corneal surface. Normal values are below 21 mm with asymmetry exceeding 2 mm being clinically significant.<br><br>Serial Hertel measurements monitor progression of proptosis and treatment response. Readings above 24 mm indicate significant proptosis. The instrument rests on both lateral orbital rims simultaneously. Hertel exophthalmometry readings and their normal asymmetry limit are a classic measurable orbital parameter.<br><br>Axial length (A) is measured by A-scan biometry. Eyelid retraction (B) is measured in millimetres from the limbus. IOP (C) is measured by tonometry. Corneal curvature (D) is measured by keratometry.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old with inactive thyroid eye disease has 28 mm of proptosis bilaterally with significant corneal exposure. He has diplopia in all positions. What is the correct sequence of surgical rehabilitation?","o":["Eyelid surgery first then strabismus then decompression","Strabismus surgery first then decompression then eyelid surgery","Decompression then eyelid surgery then strabismus surgery","Decompression then strabismus surgery then eyelid surgery","All three surgeries simultaneously in one session"],"a":3,"e":"The correct sequence in thyroid eye disease surgical rehabilitation is orbital decompression first to reduce proptosis, then strabismus surgery to address diplopia which may change after decompression, and finally eyelid surgery to correct retraction and lagophthalmos.<br><br>This sequence is critical as each prior step changes the surgical outcome of the subsequent procedure.<br><br>Eyelid first (A) is incorrect as the eyelid position changes after decompression and strabismus correction. Strabismus first (B) is incorrect. Eyelid before strabismus (C) is incorrect. Simultaneous surgery (E) prevents proper sequential optimisation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 38-year-old presents with unilateral non-axial proptosis displaced inferiorly. CT shows a superotemporal mass with bony expansion but no erosion. He has had a slow painless course over years. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Lacrimal gland carcinoma","Orbital lymphoma","Pleomorphic adenoma of the lacrimal gland","Dermoid cyst","Orbital cavernous haemangioma"],"a":2,"e":"Pleomorphic adenoma is the most common benign epithelial lacrimal gland tumour. It presents with painless slow-growing proptosis displaced inferomedially. CT shows a well-defined superotemporal mass with bony expansion but no erosion.<br><br>Complete surgical excision without violating the capsule is mandatory. Incisional biopsy is contraindicated as it risks malignant transformation. Recurrence after incomplete excision is common.<br><br>Lacrimal gland carcinoma (A) is painful with bony erosion. Orbital lymphoma (B) is moulded with salmon-pink subconjunctival appearance. Dermoid cyst (D) occurs at suture lines. Cavernous haemangioma (E) is intraconal.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 70-year-old man presents with rapidly progressive bilateral proptosis, ptosis, and RAPD. CT shows bilateral apical orbital masses. He has a known history of lung cancer. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Bilateral orbital pseudotumour","Bilateral thyroid eye disease","Bilateral cavernous haemangioma","Bilateral orbital metastasis","Bilateral orbital lymphoma"],"a":3,"e":"Bilateral orbital metastases in a patient with known lung cancer present with rapidly progressive proptosis, diplopia, and visual loss. Lung and breast cancers are the most common primary tumours causing orbital metastasis.<br><br>Scirrhous breast carcinoma metastasis characteristically causes enophthalmos from fibrotic retraction rather than proptosis. Radiotherapy palliates symptoms. Systemic oncological treatment addresses the primary disease.<br><br>Bilateral pseudotumour (A) is rare and painful. TED (B) shows enlarged muscles on CT. Bilateral cavernous haemangioma (C) is rare with slow onset. Bilateral orbital lymphoma (E) occurs in older adults but without the rapid progression seen in metastasis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old woman with breast cancer presents with right enophthalmos, restricted motility, and ipsilateral ptosis. CT shows a right orbital mass with adjacent bone sclerosis. What is the mechanism of enophthalmos in this condition?","o":["Orbital fat atrophy from radiation therapy","Globe displacement from bony defect","Orbital varix causing intermittent volume change","Hypothyroidism causing fat volume reduction","Fibrotic retraction of orbital fat by scirrhous breast carcinoma metastasis"],"a":4,"e":"Scirrhous breast carcinoma metastasis to the orbit causes enophthalmos through fibrotic retraction of orbital fat and connective tissue rather than proptosis.<br><br>The restricted motility results from fibrotic involvement of extraocular muscles. Radiotherapy and hormonal therapy are used for palliation.<br><br>Radiation-induced fat atrophy (A) is a late effect not the presenting mechanism. Globe displacement from bony defect (B) is not the mechanism. Orbital varix (C) causes intermittent proptosis. Hypothyroidism (D) does not cause enophthalmos.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with proptosis that increases on bending forward or performing Valsalva manoeuvre. CT shows an irregular vascular lesion that changes size. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Carotid-cavernous fistula","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Orbital pseudotumour","Orbital varix","Lymphangioma"],"a":3,"e":"Orbital varix is a venous vascular malformation that enlarges dramatically on Valsalva manoeuvre or bending forward due to increased venous pressure causing blood to pool in the varix. CT with Valsalva confirms the diagnosis by showing the enlarged lesion.<br><br>Treatment is surgical excision for symptomatic cases or those threatening vision. Asymptomatic cases are monitored. Acute haemorrhage into the varix causes sudden painful proptosis.<br><br>Carotid-cavernous fistula (A) causes pulsatile proptosis with bruit. Cavernous haemangioma (B) does not change size with Valsalva. Pseudotumour (C) is painful. Lymphangioma (E) expands after upper respiratory infections from haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 20-year-old presents with acute onset proptosis following an upper respiratory tract infection. CT shows a multilocular irregular orbital mass with no contrast enhancement and areas of haemorrhage. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital abscess","Orbital lymphoma","Cavernous haemangioma","Dermoid cyst rupture","Lymphangioma with spontaneous haemorrhage"],"a":4,"e":"Orbital lymphangioma is a vascular hamartoma that expands acutely after upper respiratory infections due to lymphoid hyperplasia or spontaneous haemorrhage creating chocolate cysts. CT shows a multilocular irregular mass with haemorrhagic components without contrast enhancement.<br><br>Management of acute haemorrhagic proptosis includes drainage of the blood cyst. Complete surgical excision is difficult due to the infiltrative nature without defined capsule.<br><br>Orbital abscess (A) shows enhancement and systemic infection. Orbital lymphoma (B) is moulded and painless. Cavernous haemangioma (C) is encapsulated with contrast enhancement. Dermoid cyst rupture (D) causes acute inflammation but in a different location.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with proptosis and a violet discolouration of the eyelids. CT shows an intraconal mass with bone erosion. Biopsy reveals plasmacytic infiltrate. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital lymphoma","Orbital pseudotumour","IgG4-related orbital disease","Orbital metastasis","Cavernous haemangioma"],"a":2,"e":"IgG4-related orbital disease causes proptosis, lacrimal gland enlargement, and a violet discolouration of the eyelids from dense plasmacytic infiltrate. Serum IgG4 levels are elevated. Histology shows storiform fibrosis and IgG4-positive plasma cells.<br><br>Systemic corticosteroids are first-line treatment. Rituximab is used for refractory cases. Systemic workup is required as IgG4-related disease affects multiple organ systems simultaneously.<br><br>Orbital lymphoma (A) is a distinct entity with different histology. Orbital pseudotumour (B) responds to steroids but lacks IgG4 histological features. Orbital metastasis (D) has a known primary. Cavernous haemangioma (E) is encapsulated.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 48-year-old with thyroid eye disease has lid retraction and lagophthalmos. Which sign describes lid lag on downgaze in thyroid eye disease?","o":["Stellwag sign","Joffroy sign","Von Graefe sign","Dalrymple sign","Möbius sign"],"a":2,"e":"Von Graefe sign is the lag of the upper eyelid behind the globe on downgaze in thyroid eye disease, caused by sympathetic overactivity and fibrosis of the levator palpebrae. It produces a rim of sclera visible above the cornea on downgaze.<br><br>Dalrymple sign is upper lid retraction in primary gaze. Stellwag sign is infrequent blinking. Joffroy sign is absent wrinkling of the forehead on upgaze. Möbius sign is convergence weakness.<br><br>Stellwag sign (A) is infrequent blinking. Joffroy sign (B) is absent frontalis activation on upgaze. Dalrymple sign (D) is upper lid retraction in primary gaze. Möbius sign (E) is impaired convergence in thyroid eye disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old presents with ptosis, proptosis, and a bruit over the orbit. He also has dilated conjunctival vessels and pulsatile proptosis. Which investigation confirms the diagnosis of carotid-cavernous fistula?","o":["CT orbit plain","MRI orbit without contrast","Colour Doppler imaging of the superior ophthalmic vein","Hertel exophthalmometry","Orbital ultrasound A-scan"],"a":2,"e":"Colour Doppler imaging demonstrating reversed arterialized flow in the dilated superior ophthalmic vein is diagnostic of carotid-cavernous fistula. The normal low-velocity venous flow is replaced by high-velocity pulsatile arterial flow.<br><br>CT angiography or conventional digital subtraction angiography is the gold standard for treatment planning before endovascular embolisation. A pulsatile proptosis with an audible bruit after trauma is the hallmark presentation of a carotid-cavernous fistula.<br><br>Plain CT (A) shows dilated superior ophthalmic vein but not flow direction. MRI without contrast (B) is insufficient. Hertel exophthalmometry (D) measures proptosis only. Orbital A-scan ultrasound (E) does not assess vascular flow.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 10-year-old presents with proptosis and ptosis since birth. CT shows a well-defined orbital mass that does not enhance. It expands the bony orbit. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Rhabdomyosarcoma","Optic nerve glioma","Orbital neurofibroma","Lymphangioma","Orbital cavernous haemangioma"],"a":3,"e":"Orbital lymphangioma is present from early childhood, causing slowly progressive proptosis and ptosis. It is a non-enhancing orbital mass on CT that may expand the bony orbit over years from slow volume increase.<br><br>Unlike varix it does not change with Valsalva. Haemorrhage into the lesion causes acute painful proptosis. Complete excision is difficult due to infiltrative non-encapsulated growth.<br><br>Rhabdomyosarcoma (A) grows rapidly. Optic nerve glioma (B) is fusiform along the nerve. Orbital neurofibroma (C) is associated with NF1 and causes bony defects. Cavernous haemangioma (E) occurs in adults and shows contrast enhancement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old woman presents with proptosis and bilateral lacrimal gland enlargement. CT shows bilateral enlarged lacrimal glands. Serum ACE is elevated. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Lymphoma of the lacrimal gland bilaterally","Sjögren syndrome with bilateral lacrimal enlargement","Sarcoidosis with bilateral lacrimal gland infiltration","IgG4-related orbital disease","Bilateral dacryoadenitis from viral infection"],"a":2,"e":"Sarcoidosis commonly involves the lacrimal glands causing bilateral painless enlargement with proptosis. Elevated serum ACE, chest CT showing hilar lymphadenopathy, and biopsy showing non-caseating granulomas confirm the diagnosis.<br><br>Systemic corticosteroids are the first-line treatment. Lacrimal gland involvement may also cause dry eye from reduced tear secretion.<br><br>Bilateral lymphoma (A) is possible but ACE elevation points to sarcoidosis. Sjögren syndrome (B) causes dry eyes and mouth without ACE elevation. IgG4-related disease (D) requires IgG4 staining. Viral dacryoadenitis (E) is painful and unilateral.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old smoker with Graves disease is counselled about risk factors for thyroid eye disease. Which is the single most important modifiable risk factor for developing severe TED?","o":["High serum T4 levels","Elevated TRAb titre","Female sex","Smoking","Radioiodine treatment"],"a":3,"e":"Smoking is the single most important modifiable risk factor for thyroid eye disease. It increases the risk of developing TED fourfold and is associated with more severe disease, higher recurrence rate, and poorer response to treatment.<br><br>Smoking cessation is the most important advice for any patient with Graves disease. Radioiodine therapy may exacerbate TED and prophylactic steroids are given to smokers undergoing radioiodine.<br><br>High T4 (A) reflects disease activity but is not the key modifiable factor. TRAb (B) correlates with severity but is not modifiable. Female sex (C) is non-modifiable. Radioiodine (E) is a risk but smoking is the primary modifiable risk factor.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old man presents with bilateral axial proptosis, upper lid retraction of 3 mm bilaterally, chemosis, and injected plica. He has elevated T3 and T4. What is the most specific clinical feature of thyroid eye disease on lid examination?","o":["Complete ptosis","Horner ptosis","Upper lid retraction with scleral show","Marcus Gunn jaw-winking ptosis","Frontalis overaction"],"a":2,"e":"Upper eyelid retraction with superior scleral show in primary gaze is the most characteristic and specific sign of thyroid eye disease. It results from sympathetic overactivity and levator fibrosis, or from inferior rectus fibrosis causing compensatory superior rectus overaction.<br><br>Normal upper lid covers approximately 1 to 2 mm of the superior cornea. Scleral show above the limbus in primary gaze indicates pathological lid retraction.<br><br>Complete ptosis (A) is the opposite of retraction. Horner ptosis (B) is partial ptosis from sympathetic loss. Marcus Gunn (D) is congenital ptosis with synkinesis. Frontalis overaction (E) occurs to compensate for ptosis not retraction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old with bilateral orbital metastases from breast cancer presents with restricted upgaze. Which extraocular muscle is most commonly infiltrated by orbital metastases causing restriction?","o":["Superior rectus bilateral involvement","Lateral rectus muscle fibrosis","Inferior rectus or medial rectus infiltration","Superior oblique tendon involvement","Levator palpebrae superioris infiltration"],"a":2,"e":"Orbital metastases most commonly infiltrate the inferior and medial recti, causing restricted upgaze and abduction respectively. Scirrhous breast carcinoma characteristically causes fibrotic restriction of these muscles with enophthalmos.<br><br>CT shows an irregular poorly marginated mass associated with the muscle belly. Radiotherapy reduces the metastatic volume and may partially restore motility.<br><br>Superior rectus bilateral involvement (A) is less common. Lateral rectus fibrosis (B) is the least affected muscle. Superior oblique tendon (D) is rarely involved by metastasis. Levator infiltration (E) causes ptosis from direct involvement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old presents with unilateral proptosis and a pulsatile orbital mass. No bruit is audible. CT shows an enlarged orbit with bone erosion at the roof. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Carotid-cavernous fistula","Orbital lymphoma","Orbital pseudotumour","Encephalocele transmitting cerebral pulsations","Orbital varix"],"a":3,"e":"Pulsatile proptosis without a bruit with bony defect at the orbital roof indicates an encephalocele or meningocele transmitting cerebral pulsations directly through the bony defect into the orbit. CT confirms orbital roof defect communicating with the cranial cavity.<br><br>Neurofibromatosis type 1 is classically associated with orbital roof dysplasia causing pulsatile proptosis through transmitted brain pulsations.<br><br>CCF (A) causes bruit. Orbital lymphoma (B) is non-pulsatile. Orbital pseudotumour (C) is painful without bony defect. Orbital varix (E) increases with Valsalva without bony roof erosion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 6-year-old presents with a midline orbital swelling that increases when the child cries. Transillumination is positive. CT shows a cystic midline lesion with a nasal stalk. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Dermoid cyst","Orbital lymphangioma","Dacryocele","Nasal glioma","Nasolacrimal duct cyst"],"a":4,"e":"Nasolacrimal duct cyst presents in infants and young children as a medial canthal swelling that increases with crying or Valsalva from increased nasopharyngeal pressure transmitted through the patent nasolacrimal canal into the cyst.<br><br>Nasal endoscopy confirms the intranasal component. Treatment involves probing and marsupialization of the intranasal cyst. Simple probing without intranasal marsupialization leads to high recurrence.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) does not increase with crying. Lymphangioma (B) expands after upper respiratory infections. Dacryocele (C) is at birth and does not have a nasal stalk. Nasal glioma (D) is a solid lesion without connection to the ventricles.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 48-year-old presents with proptosis, chemosis, and elevated IOP bilaterally. Carotid angiography confirms an indirect dural carotid-cavernous fistula. What is the most appropriate initial management?","o":["Urgent surgical ligation of the internal carotid artery","Observation as indirect CCF often resolves spontaneously","Immediate orbital decompression surgery","Intravenous heparin anticoagulation","Orbital radiotherapy to the cavernous sinus"],"a":1,"e":"Indirect or dural carotid-cavernous fistulas are low-flow connections between dural branches and the cavernous sinus. Up to 70% resolve spontaneously with observation. Spontaneous closure is monitored with serial Doppler imaging.<br><br>Endovascular embolisation is reserved for cases with progressive visual loss, uncontrolled IOP, or intractable diplopia that fail to resolve spontaneously.<br><br>Surgical ICA ligation (A) is a historical treatment not used now. Immediate decompression (C) is not indicated for indirect CCF. Heparin (D) is not standard treatment. Orbital radiotherapy (E) has no role in CCF management.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old presents with painless unilateral proptosis. MRI shows a well-defined lobulated lesion within the lacrimal gland fossa with smooth bony expansion. No contrast enhancement is seen on T1. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Adenoid cystic carcinoma","Orbital lymphoma","Pleomorphic adenoma of the lacrimal gland","Dermoid cyst","Orbital cavernous haemangioma"],"a":2,"e":"Pleomorphic adenoma presents as a painless slow-growing superotemporal mass with smooth bony expansion on CT and MRI without bony erosion. T1 MRI shows heterogeneous signal. Surgical excision through a lateral orbitotomy without violating the capsule is essential.<br><br>Biopsy is absolutely contraindicated before excision as it risks capsule violation causing malignant transformation or recurrence.<br><br>Adenoid cystic carcinoma (A) causes bony erosion with pain. Orbital lymphoma (B) is moulded and often subconjunctival. Dermoid cyst (D) occurs at suture lines in younger patients. Cavernous haemangioma (E) is intraconal with marked T2 hyperintensity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old woman presents with progressive bilateral proptosis and restriction of upgaze. She was euthyroid on examination. Serum T3, T4, and TSH are normal. TRAb is elevated. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital pseudotumour bilaterally","Euthyroid Graves orbitopathy","Bilateral orbital lymphoma","Sarcoidosis with bilateral orbital infiltration","IgG4-related bilateral orbital disease"],"a":1,"e":"Euthyroid Graves orbitopathy presents with the typical features of thyroid eye disease including bilateral proptosis and extraocular muscle restriction but with normal thyroid function tests. Elevated TRAb confirms the autoimmune aetiology.<br><br>Thyroid function may remain normal or become abnormal later. Management follows the same principles as TED with active Graves disease. TRAb monitoring tracks disease activity.<br><br>Bilateral orbital pseudotumour (A) is painful. Bilateral lymphoma (C) shows a moulded mass on MRI. Sarcoidosis (D) has elevated ACE. IgG4-related disease (E) shows elevated serum IgG4 and storiform fibrosis on biopsy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old man with proptosis and periorbital oedema is found on biopsy to have storiform fibrosis and numerous IgG4-positive plasma cells. Serum IgG4 is markedly elevated. What is the treatment?","o":["Surgical excision of the orbital mass","Orbital radiotherapy first-line","High-dose systemic corticosteroids","Intravenous antibiotics","Observation only"],"a":2,"e":"IgG4-related orbital disease responds dramatically to systemic corticosteroids confirming the diagnosis. Treatment begins with prednisolone 40 mg daily with gradual tapering. Rituximab is used for refractory or steroid-dependent cases.<br><br>Systemic workup is essential as IgG4-related disease affects pancreas, kidneys, salivary glands, and other organs simultaneously requiring multidisciplinary management.<br><br>Surgical excision (A) does not cure IgG4-related disease. Orbital radiotherapy (B) is used for orbital lymphoma. Intravenous antibiotics (D) treat orbital cellulitis. Observation only (E) risks progressive fibrosis causing permanent proptosis and visual loss.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old man presents with unilateral proptosis, optic disc swelling, and choroidal folds on fundoscopy. CT shows a hyperdense homogeneous mass adjacent to the globe with scleral thickening. Orbital ultrasound shows a T-sign. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital lymphoma","Orbital cellulitis","Thyroid eye disease","Posterior scleritis","Orbital cavernous haemangioma"],"a":3,"e":"Posterior scleritis causes proptosis, choroidal folds, disc oedema, exudative retinal detachment, and severe pain worsening with eye movement. The T-sign on B-scan ultrasound representing fluid in Tenon space around the optic nerve is pathognomonic.<br><br>Systemic NSAIDs are first-line. Systemic steroids and immunosuppression treat severe cases. Underlying systemic vasculitis must be excluded in all patients presenting with posterior scleritis. Optic disc swelling with proptosis in thyroid eye disease signals compressive optic neuropathy demanding urgent action.<br><br>Orbital lymphoma (A) is painless. Orbital cellulitis (B) causes fever. TED (C) is bilateral without Tenon space fluid. Cavernous haemangioma (E) is an encapsulated intraconal lesion without the T-sign.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old presents with bilateral proptosis and night blindness. Fundoscopy shows bone-spicule retinal pigmentation and pale optic discs. ERG is extinguished. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Thyroid eye disease with optic neuropathy","Orbital pseudotumour bilaterally","Orbital cavernous haemangioma bilaterally","Orbital lymphoma bilaterally","Orbital involvement in retinitis pigmentosa"],"a":4,"e":"Retinitis pigmentosa is not primarily an orbital condition but in severe cases causes bilateral enophthalmos from loss of orbital fat and orbital soft tissue atrophy. Night blindness, bone-spicule pigmentation, and extinguished ERG confirm RP.<br><br>This question tests understanding that retinal conditions can occasionally present to orbital clinics with bilateral enophthalmos mimicking orbital pathology. Bilateral proptosis with night blindness pointing to a vitamin-related orbital infiltrate is a classic distinguishing clue.<br><br>TED (A) causes proptosis not enophthalmos with retinal changes. Bilateral pseudotumour (B) is painful. Bilateral cavernous haemangioma (C) is very rare. Bilateral orbital lymphoma (D) shows moulded masses on CT.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old man with thyroid eye disease has upper eyelid retraction of 4 mm. What is the first-line treatment for lid retraction in the acute active phase of thyroid eye disease?","o":["Surgical lid lengthening immediately","Botulinum toxin injection into the levator or Muller muscle","Lateral tarsorrhaphy","Topical guanethidine drops to block sympathetic tone","Full-thickness skin grafting to the upper lid"],"a":1,"e":"Botulinum toxin injected into the levator palpebrae or Muller muscle temporarily reduces upper lid retraction in the active phase of TED, improving ocular surface exposure and corneal protection. The effect lasts three to four months.<br><br>Surgical lid lengthening is performed only in the inactive stable phase of thyroid eye disease. Botulinum toxin buys time during the active inflammatory phase.<br><br>Surgical lid lengthening (A) is for inactive disease. Tarsorrhaphy (C) protects the cornea but does not treat retraction. Guanethidine (D) reduces sympathetic tone but causes irritation. Skin grafting (E) is for cicatricial lid changes not TED retraction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old presents with proptosis and a choroidal mass on fundoscopy. B-scan shows a dome-shaped choroidal mass with low internal reflectivity and acoustic hollowness. The T-sign is absent. What is the likely diagnosis?","o":["Posterior scleritis","Choroidal metastasis","Orbital pseudotumour compressing the globe","Orbital lymphoma with choroidal invasion","Uveal melanoma with secondary orbital extension"],"a":4,"e":"Large uveal melanoma can erode through the sclera causing orbital extension with proptosis. Fundoscopy shows the intraocular component while CT reveals extrascleral extension. Low internal reflectivity and acoustic hollowness on B-scan are characteristic of melanoma.<br><br>Management of orbital extension requires enucleation or exenteration depending on extent. Liver metastasis is the most significant systemic complication requiring regular monitoring.<br><br>Posterior scleritis (A) shows T-sign. Choroidal metastasis (B) shows high internal reflectivity on B-scan. Orbital pseudotumour (C) does not invade through the sclera. Orbital lymphoma (D) is rare to invade through the sclera.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 3-year-old presents with rapidly progressive proptosis. MRI shows a heterogeneous intraconal mass. Biopsy reveals spindle-shaped cells with interlacing fascicles and cross-striations. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital lymphoma","Optic nerve glioma","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Optic nerve sheath meningioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma embryonal type"],"a":4,"e":"Embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common subtype in children. Histology shows spindle-shaped cells with cross-striations confirming skeletal muscle differentiation. It is the most common primary orbital malignancy in children under 10 years.<br><br>Multiagent chemotherapy combined with external beam radiotherapy achieves remission in most cases. Surgical exenteration is rarely required. Five-year survival exceeds 90% for localised orbital disease.<br><br>Orbital lymphoma (A) occurs in adults. Optic nerve glioma (B) is fusiform along the nerve. Cavernous haemangioma (C) is encapsulated in adults. Optic nerve sheath meningioma (D) shows tram-track enhancement not cross-striations.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old woman with TED undergoes orbital decompression. Which wall is most commonly removed during balanced orbital decompression?","o":["Orbital roof and lateral wall","Medial wall only","Lateral wall only","Medial wall and floor combined","Orbital roof alone"],"a":3,"e":"Balanced medial wall and floor decompression is the most commonly performed orbital decompression for thyroid eye disease. Removing both walls allows the orbital contents to prolapse medially and inferiorly reducing proptosis by 3 to 5 mm per wall removed.<br><br>Balanced decompression reduces the risk of postoperative diplopia compared to single-wall decompression. Lateral wall decompression is added for greater proptosis reduction.<br><br>Orbital roof and lateral wall (A) is not the standard approach. Medial wall only (B) gives limited decompression. Lateral wall only (C) gives less decompression. Orbital roof alone (E) risks CSF leak and is not standard.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 9-year-old presents with unilateral proptosis and a palpable superotemporal orbital mass. He has six café-au-lait spots and axillary freckling. What is the most likely orbital diagnosis?","o":["Orbital dermoid cyst","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Plexiform neurofibroma of the orbit","Orbital lymphoma"],"a":3,"e":"Plexiform neurofibroma in NF1 causes progressive orbital and periorbital swelling with an S-shaped ptosis. Combined with café-au-lait spots and axillary freckling the diagnosis is NF1. It infiltrates diffusely making complete excision impossible.<br><br>CT or MRI shows an infiltrative non-encapsulated mass. The orbital roof may be dysplastic causing pulsatile proptosis from transmitted brain pulsations.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) occurs at suture lines. Cavernous haemangioma (B) occurs in adults. Rhabdomyosarcoma (C) presents acutely without NF1 features. Orbital lymphoma (E) occurs in older adults.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with bilateral proptosis of 26 mm and exposure keratopathy. He has no pain, normal vision, and his disease has been inactive for 18 months. What is the most appropriate management?","o":["High-dose intravenous methylprednisolone","Orbital radiotherapy","Observation only with lubricants","Bilateral orbital decompression surgery","Teprotumumab infusions"],"a":3,"e":"Inactive thyroid eye disease with significant proptosis causing exposure keratopathy requires orbital decompression surgery. Surgery is performed in the stable inactive phase after at least six months of disease stability.<br><br>Proptosis reduction of 3 to 5 mm per wall decompressed protects the cornea and improves cosmesis. Diplopia may worsen after decompression requiring subsequent strabismus surgery.<br><br>Intravenous methylprednisolone (A) is for active disease. Orbital radiotherapy (B) is for active disease reducing inflammation. Lubricants alone (C) are insufficient for 26 mm proptosis with keratopathy. Teprotumumab (E) is for active moderate-to-severe TED.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old presents with acute painful proptosis, fever, and periorbital redness following a dental abscess. Which organism most commonly causes orbital cellulitis in adults?","o":["Haemophilus influenzae","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Staphylococcus aureus","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Anaerobic polymicrobial infection"],"a":2,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus and Streptococcus species are the most common causative organisms in adult orbital cellulitis. Dental source infections are often polymicrobial including anaerobes. MRSA must be considered in hospital-acquired or community-resistant cases.<br><br>Broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics covering gram-positive organisms and anaerobes including co-amoxiclav or piperacillin-tazobactam are initiated empirically while awaiting culture results.<br><br>Haemophilus influenzae (A) was the most common cause in pre-vaccination children but is now rare. Streptococcus pneumoniae (B) is common but not specifically associated with dental source. Pseudomonas (D) occurs in immunocompromised patients. Anaerobic infection (E) is a description not a specific organism.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 15-year-old presents with proptosis, upward displacement of the globe, and restricted upgaze. CT shows an irregular mass in the inferior orbit with bony destruction. Biopsy reveals eosinophilic infiltrate and Langerhans cells with Birbeck granules on electron microscopy. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital lymphoma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Orbital metastasis","Eosinophilic granuloma of the orbit","Lacrimal gland adenoid cystic carcinoma"],"a":3,"e":"Eosinophilic granuloma is a form of Langerhans cell histiocytosis affecting the orbital bones, most commonly the frontal bone superolaterally. Birbeck granules on electron microscopy confirm Langerhans cell origin. It presents in children with orbital swelling and bony destruction on CT.<br><br>Treatment includes low-dose radiotherapy, curettage, or intralesional steroids. Systemic workup excludes multifocal Langerhans cell histiocytosis.<br><br>Orbital lymphoma (A) occurs in adults. Rhabdomyosarcoma (B) is intraconal without eosinophilic infiltrate. Orbital metastasis (C) occurs in adults with known primary. Adenoid cystic carcinoma (E) arises from the lacrimal gland in adults.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old woman with known non-Hodgkin's lymphoma develops bilateral orbital masses. MRI shows bilateral enhancing extraconal masses moulded to the orbital walls. What is the appropriate treatment?","o":["Surgical excision bilaterally","Intravenous antibiotics","Systemic corticosteroids alone","Combined systemic chemotherapy and local radiotherapy","Observation with annual MRI"],"a":3,"e":"Secondary orbital lymphoma from systemic NHL requires systemic chemotherapy including rituximab-based CHOP regimens combined with local orbital radiotherapy. Local radiotherapy achieves excellent regional control while systemic chemotherapy addresses the disseminated disease.<br><br>Orbital biopsy confirms the histological subtype guiding chemotherapy selection. Regular haematological follow-up monitors treatment response and detects relapse.<br><br>Surgical excision (A) does not cure lymphoma. Intravenous antibiotics (B) treat infection. Steroids alone (C) are insufficient and risk masking lymphoma. Observation alone (E) is inappropriate for systemic NHL with orbital involvement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with bilateral proptosis, dry eyes, and dry mouth. CT shows bilateral enlarged lacrimal glands and parotid glands. What investigation is most useful to confirm the diagnosis?","o":["Serum ACE level","Anti-SS-A and anti-SS-B antibodies","TRAb level","Serum IgG4 level","Biopsy of the lacrimal gland"],"a":1,"e":"Sjögren syndrome causes bilateral lacrimal and parotid gland enlargement with dry eyes and dry mouth. Anti-SS-A and anti-SS-B antibodies are the specific serological markers confirming primary Sjögren syndrome.<br><br>Schirmer test confirms reduced tear secretion. Minor salivary gland biopsy showing focal lymphocytic sialadenitis provides histological confirmation of the diagnosis.<br><br>Serum ACE (A) confirms sarcoidosis. TRAb (C) confirms Graves disease. Serum IgG4 (D) confirms IgG4-related disease. Lacrimal gland biopsy (E) is more invasive and reserved for uncertain cases.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old presents with acute bilateral orbital swelling and fever following influenza vaccination. CT shows periorbital oedema without abscess or restricted motility. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital cellulitis","Preseptal cellulitis bilateral","Orbital pseudotumour bilateral","Allergic reaction causing bilateral preseptal oedema","Cavernous sinus thrombosis"],"a":3,"e":"Bilateral preseptal oedema without restricted motility, fever above 38.5, or CT changes suggesting septal involvement indicates an allergic or hypersensitivity reaction. Post-vaccination reactions are a recognised cause. Normal eye movements and absence of proptosis confirm the preseptal location.<br><br>Antihistamines and observation are appropriate. Bilateral presentation makes infectious orbital cellulitis extremely unlikely.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (A) is typically unilateral with proptosis and restricted motility. Bilateral preseptal cellulitis (B) is very rare. Bilateral pseudotumour (C) is painful with CT changes. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (E) causes bilateral sixth nerve palsies with sepsis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 70-year-old man presents with proptosis, an afferent pupillary defect, choroidal folds, and optociliary shunt vessels on the disc. MRI shows an enhancing mass along the optic nerve. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Optic nerve glioma","Optic nerve sheath meningioma","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Orbital lymphoma","Posterior scleritis"],"a":1,"e":"Optic nerve sheath meningioma classically presents with the triad of progressive visual loss, optic atrophy, and optociliary shunt vessels. MRI with gadolinium shows the classic tram-track enhancement pattern with central nerve sparing within the meningeal sleeve.<br><br>Fractionated stereotactic radiotherapy is the treatment of choice preserving both vision and halting tumour growth with fewer side effects than surgical resection.<br><br>Optic nerve glioma (A) occurs in children and shows fusiform nerve expansion. Cavernous haemangioma (C) is intraconal without nerve involvement. Orbital lymphoma (D) is moulded and extraconal. Posterior scleritis (E) shows the T-sign on ultrasound.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with painful left proptosis and ophthalmoplegia. He has a history of sinusitis. MRI shows enhancement along the orbital walls, periorbital fat, and cavernous sinus bilaterally. What is the most urgent concern?","o":["Orbital pseudotumour requiring steroids","IgG4-related orbital disease requiring rituximab","Orbital lymphoma requiring radiotherapy","Fungal sinusitis with orbital and cavernous sinus extension","Thyroid eye disease decompensation"],"a":3,"e":"Invasive fungal sinusitis, particularly Aspergillus or Mucor in a diabetic or immunocompromised patient, can rapidly extend into the orbit and cavernous sinus. This constitutes an ophthalmic and neurological emergency with high mortality.<br><br>Urgent surgical debridement, antifungal therapy with liposomal amphotericin B, and optimisation of the underlying immunosuppression are required simultaneously.<br><br>Orbital pseudotumour (A) responds to steroids and lacks sinus extension bilaterally. IgG4-related disease (B) is subacute. Orbital lymphoma (C) does not cause acute sinus involvement. TED (E) does not cause cavernous sinus enhancement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 58-year-old woman with bilateral thyroid eye disease undergoes strabismus surgery for vertical diplopia. The forced duction test is positive. What does a positive forced duction test indicate?","o":["Paretic muscle weakness causing underaction","Supranuclear gaze palsy","Restrictive myopathy from fibrotic muscle causing mechanical limitation","Myasthenia gravis causing fatigable weakness","Orbital cellulitis restricting movement by inflammation"],"a":2,"e":"A positive forced duction test confirms mechanical restriction of eye movement from a fibrotic muscle, typically the inferior or medial rectus in thyroid eye disease. This distinguishes restrictive from paretic strabismus.<br><br>Under anaesthesia, the globe cannot be moved passively in the direction of gaze restriction when the fibrotic muscle acts as a tether confirming the restrictive aetiology before recession surgery.<br><br>Paretic weakness (A) gives a negative forced duction test. Supranuclear gaze palsy (B) shows normal ductions. Myasthenia gravis (D) gives a negative forced duction test. Orbital cellulitis (E) causes painful restriction with a positive forced duction from periorbital infiltration.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with painless proptosis and is found to have a right orbital floor fracture from previous trauma. The eye is displaced inferiorly. What is the term for inferior displacement of the globe?","o":["Enophthalmos","Proptosis","Hyperglobus","Hypoglobus","Exophthalmos"],"a":3,"e":"Hypoglobus refers to inferior displacement of the globe from its normal position in the orbit. Orbital floor fracture with herniation of orbital contents into the maxillary sinus causes both enophthalmos and hypoglobus.<br><br>Diplopia results from inferior rectus entrapment in the fracture site. Early surgical repair within two weeks prevents permanent muscle fibrosis and diplopia.<br><br>Enophthalmos (A) is posterior displacement. Proptosis and exophthalmos (B) and (E) are anterior displacement. Hyperglobus (C) is superior displacement from inferior orbital mass or floor fracture repair overcorrection.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 32-year-old woman with known TED on no treatment is found to have an IOP of 28 mmHg in upgaze and 16 mmHg in primary gaze. What causes the IOP elevation on upgaze in TED?","o":["Increased aqueous production in upgaze","Mechanical compression of the globe by the fibrotic inferior rectus in upgaze","Elevated episcleral venous pressure from orbital congestion","Steroid-induced trabecular dysfunction","Angle closure from forward displacement of the lens-iris diaphragm"],"a":1,"e":"The fibrotic inferior rectus in TED acts as a tether. On upgaze, stretching of the fibrotic inferior rectus compresses the globe mechanically increasing IOP. This is the most common cause of elevated IOP on upgaze in thyroid eye disease.<br><br>This phenomenon can mimic glaucoma if IOP is measured in upgaze only. Measuring IOP in primary gaze gives the correct baseline pressure.<br><br>Increased aqueous production (A) does not occur on upgaze. Steroid-induced glaucoma (D) is elevated in all positions. Elevated episcleral venous pressure (C) causes elevated IOP in all positions. Angle closure (E) is not the mechanism of positional IOP change in TED.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old presents with proptosis and is found on CT to have a mass in the superior nasal quadrant of the orbit with scalloping of the adjacent bone. No periosteal reaction. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Lacrimal gland carcinoma","Orbital dermoid cyst","Mucocele of the frontoethmoidal sinus","Orbital lymphoma","Rhabdomyosarcoma"],"a":2,"e":"Frontoethmoidal mucocele expands gradually eroding adjacent orbital bone by pressure necrosis producing smooth scalloped bony defects without periosteal reaction on CT. It causes painless proptosis with inferior and lateral globe displacement.<br><br>Surgical marsupialization via an endoscopic nasal approach or combined open approach drains the mucocele and prevents recurrence. Mucoceles arise from obstruction of sinus drainage.<br><br>Lacrimal gland carcinoma (A) is superotemporal with irregular bony erosion and pain. Dermoid cyst (B) is at suture lines. Orbital lymphoma (D) is moulded without bony erosion. Rhabdomyosarcoma (E) grows rapidly in children.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with bilateral proptosis and engorged orbital and facial veins. He has a history of blunt head trauma six months ago. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Bilateral orbital pseudotumour","IgG4-related bilateral orbital disease","Dural arteriovenous malformation with orbital venous hypertension","Bilateral cavernous haemangioma","Orbital lymphoma bilaterally"],"a":2,"e":"Dural arteriovenous malformation causes venous hypertension transmitted to the orbit through the superior ophthalmic vein causing bilateral proptosis and engorgement of orbital and facial veins. The history of prior head trauma is a recognised trigger.<br><br>CT angiography or conventional angiography confirms the AVM anatomy before treatment. Endovascular embolisation or stereotactic radiosurgery are the treatment options.<br><br>Bilateral pseudotumour (A) is painful. IgG4-related disease (B) does not cause vascular engorgement. Bilateral cavernous haemangioma (D) is exceedingly rare. Bilateral orbital lymphoma (E) shows moulded masses without vascular changes.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 12-year-old boy presents with a red elevated conjunctival mass at the limbus which is vascularised, surrounded by lipid infiltration. It has been growing slowly. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Conjunctival lymphoma","Dermoid at the limbus","Pterygium","Epibulbar osseous choristoma","Conjunctival squamous cell carcinoma"],"a":1,"e":"Limbal dermoid is a choristoma containing displaced ectodermal tissue occurring most commonly at the inferotemporal limbus. It is present from birth, grows slowly, and contains hair follicles, sebaceous glands, and lipid deposits causing the characteristic white vascularised appearance.<br><br>It is associated with Goldenhar syndrome with ipsilateral preauricular appendage and hemifacial microsomia. Surgical excision is performed for visual axis encroachment or cosmesis.<br><br>Conjunctival lymphoma (A) is salmon-pink and occurs in adults. Pterygium (C) is a fibrovascular tissue growth from the nasal limbus. Epibulbar osseous choristoma (D) is calcified. Squamous cell carcinoma (E) occurs in adults with sun damage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 28-year-old woman with thyroid eye disease has a clinical activity score of 7/7. She is started on intravenous methylprednisolone. What is the maximum cumulative dose to avoid steroid-related liver toxicity?","o":["8 grams total","5 grams total","3 grams total","10 grams total","12 grams total"],"a":0,"e":"The maximum cumulative dose of intravenous methylprednisolone in thyroid eye disease is 8 grams to avoid drug-induced liver injury, which can be fatal. Standard protocols use 500 mg weekly for six weeks followed by 250 mg weekly for six weeks totalling 4.5 grams.<br><br>Liver function tests must be monitored before each dose. Acute liver failure has been reported with cumulative doses exceeding 8 grams.<br><br>3 grams (C) and 5 grams (B) are below the maximum and acceptable. 10 grams (D) and 12 grams (E) exceed the safe cumulative limit risking fatal hepatotoxicity.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old presents with a painful hard orbital mass associated with numbness of the cheek and upper teeth. CT shows bone erosion extending from the maxillary sinus superiorly into the orbit. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Orbital lymphoma","Maxillary sinus carcinoma with orbital invasion","Orbital pseudotumour","IgG4-related orbital disease","Lacrimal gland carcinoma"],"a":1,"e":"Maxillary sinus carcinoma invades superiorly through the orbital floor causing proptosis, infraorbital nerve numbness from cheek and upper teeth, and upward globe displacement. CT shows irregular bony destruction of the orbital floor.<br><br>Multimodality treatment with radical surgery and radiotherapy is required. Orbital exenteration may be necessary for extensive orbital involvement. Prognosis is poor for advanced disease.<br><br>Orbital lymphoma (A) is moulded and painless without bony erosion. Orbital pseudotumour (C) responds to steroids. IgG4-related disease (D) shows storiform fibrosis. Lacrimal gland carcinoma (E) arises from the superotemporal orbit.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old presents with unilateral proptosis and ophthalmoplegia. CT shows irregular soft tissue in the orbital apex and cavernous sinus bilaterally with enhancing tissue along the trigeminal nerve. He has lost 10 kg in six months. What must be excluded first?","o":["Lymphoma with perineural spread","IgG4-related orbital disease","Orbital pseudotumour","Sarcoidosis with orbital involvement","Tolosa-Hunt syndrome"],"a":0,"e":"Perineural spread along the trigeminal nerve with orbital and cavernous sinus involvement combined with weight loss raises strong suspicion of lymphoma or perineural malignancy. Biopsy is mandatory. Perineural spread indicates advanced disease with poor prognosis.<br><br>Systemic staging with PET-CT identifies the full extent of disease. Combined chemotherapy and radiotherapy are used for treatment of lymphoma with perineural involvement.<br><br>Orbital pseudotumour (C) is painful and responds to steroids. IgG4-related disease (B) does not cause weight loss. Sarcoidosis (D) shows elevated ACE with hilar lymphadenopathy. Tolosa-Hunt (E) responds dramatically to steroids without weight loss.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old presents with pulsatile proptosis, a bruit, and raised IOP of 35 mmHg. Anterior segment shows dilated and tortuous episcleral vessels. Which mechanism causes elevated IOP in carotid-cavernous fistula?","o":["Raised episcleral venous pressure from arterialization of the venous system","Angle closure from forward lens displacement","Primary open-angle glaucoma coincidentally","Steroid-induced trabecular dysfunction","Inflammatory trabecular meshwork obstruction"],"a":0,"e":"In carotid-cavernous fistula, high-pressure arterial blood shunts directly into the cavernous sinus and retrograde through the superior ophthalmic vein. This elevates episcleral venous pressure, reducing the pressure gradient for aqueous drainage and raising IOP.<br><br>Treatment of the fistula by endovascular embolisation normalises episcleral venous pressure and IOP in most cases without requiring separate glaucoma surgery. Pulsatile proptosis with a bruit reducible on compression is the textbook sign of an orbital arteriovenous shunt.<br><br>Steroid-induced glaucoma (D) is open-angle without episcleral vessel dilation. Angle closure (B) is not the mechanism. Coincidental POAG (C) does not explain dilated episcleral vessels. Inflammatory obstruction (E) is the mechanism in uveitic glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old presents with bilateral orbital proptosis and upper lid retraction. Thyroid function is normal. She is found to have dermatomyositis. What explains the orbital findings?","o":["Thyroid disease triggered by dermatomyositis","Orbital muscle inflammation identical to thyroid eye disease","Orbital lymphoma associated with dermatomyositis","IgG4-related orbital disease as paraneoplastic","Bilateral orbital pseudotumour"],"a":1,"e":"Dermatomyositis can cause extraocular muscle inflammation and lid retraction mimicking thyroid eye disease. The orbital myositis in dermatomyositis involves the tendinous insertions unlike TED where the muscle belly is enlarged sparing the tendons.<br><br>MRI of the orbit shows extraocular muscle tendon involvement confirming myositis rather than TED. Systemic immunosuppression treats both the systemic and orbital myositis.<br><br>Thyroid disease triggered by dermatomyositis (A) is not the explanation as thyroid function is normal. Orbital lymphoma (C) is an unrelated diagnosis. IgG4-related disease (D) has specific histological features. Bilateral pseudotumour (E) is painful.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with left proptosis and restriction of adduction. MRI shows a left medial rectus mass infiltrating the tendinous insertion and muscle belly. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Thyroid eye disease affecting medial rectus","Orbital pseudotumour myositic type","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous haemangioma","Orbital lymphoma infiltrating medial rectus"],"a":1,"e":"Orbital myositis, a subtype of orbital pseudotumour, characteristically involves the tendinous insertion unlike thyroid eye disease where the tendon is spared. It presents with acute painful restricted eye movement. The diagnosis is confirmed by dramatic response to systemic corticosteroids.<br><br>If no response to steroids, biopsy is mandatory to exclude lymphoma or IgG4-related disease which can mimic orbital pseudotumour.<br><br>Thyroid eye disease (A) spares the tendon. Rhabdomyosarcoma (C) occurs in children. Cavernous haemangioma (D) is intraconal without muscle involvement. Orbital lymphoma (E) is possible but orbital myositis responds to steroids while lymphoma does not.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 20-year-old woman presents with bilateral temporal hemianopia and bitemporal visual field defect. MRI shows a suprasellar mass expanding the sella. She has amenorrhoea and galactorrhoea. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Prolactinoma","Craniopharyngioma","Optic nerve glioma","Meningioma of the tuberculum sellae","Orbital lymphoma with chiasmal compression"],"a":0,"e":"Prolactinoma is the most common pituitary adenoma. It compresses the optic chiasm from below causing bitemporal hemianopia. Amenorrhoea and galactorrhoea from hyperprolactinaemia confirm the hormonal diagnosis.<br><br>Dopamine agonists including cabergoline or bromocriptine are first-line treatment shrinking the tumour and restoring vision. Surgical resection via transsphenoidal approach is reserved for dopamine agonist-resistant cases.<br><br>Optic nerve glioma (C) is fusiform along the nerve. Craniopharyngioma (B) causes bitemporal hemianopia but occurs in children and has calcification. Meningioma (D) grows slowly without galactorrhoea. Orbital lymphoma (E) does not compress the chiasm.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old presents with proptosis and is diagnosed with orbital pseudotumour. He is started on systemic prednisolone 80 mg daily. After 48 hours there is no improvement. What is the next step?","o":["Increase prednisolone dose to 120 mg daily","Orbital biopsy to exclude lymphoma or other diagnosis","Add orbital radiotherapy immediately","Intravenous immunoglobulin infusion","Switch to rituximab infusion"],"a":1,"e":"Failure to respond to systemic corticosteroids within 48 to 72 hours in suspected orbital pseudotumour mandates biopsy to exclude orbital lymphoma, IgG4-related disease, or other masquerade conditions that do not respond to steroids.<br><br>Approximately 25% of cases initially diagnosed as orbital pseudotumour prove to be lymphoma on biopsy following steroid failure.<br><br>Increasing prednisolone (A) risks complications without addressing the underlying diagnosis. Adding radiotherapy (C) is premature without histological confirmation. Intravenous immunoglobulin (D) has no role here. Rituximab (E) is for confirmed IgG4-related disease or lymphoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old woman presents with right proptosis and limited right gaze. CT shows an irregular right orbital mass with destruction of the right orbital wall. She has a history of frontal sinus surgery three years ago. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["Orbital pseudotumour recurrence","Orbital lymphoma post-radiotherapy","Lacrimal gland carcinoma","Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma","Post-surgical mucocele with orbital extension"],"a":4,"e":"Mucocele can develop years after sinus surgery from obstruction of sinus drainage. Gradual expansion erodes the adjacent orbital wall with smooth bony changes on CT causing progressive proptosis and motility restriction.<br><br>Endoscopic marsupialization restores sinus drainage. Combined open and endoscopic approach addresses large mucoceles with extensive orbital involvement.<br><br>Orbital pseudotumour (A) is painful without bony erosion. Orbital lymphoma (B) shows a moulded mass. Rhabdomyosarcoma (D) occurs in children with rapid onset. Lacrimal gland carcinoma (C) is superotemporal with irregular destruction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old diabetic presents with periorbital cellulitis and black nasal discharge. Serum glucose is 28 mmol/L. KOH preparation of the nasal discharge shows broad non-septate hyphae with right-angle branching. What is the treatment?","o":["Intravenous liposomal amphotericin B and urgent surgical debridement with glycaemic control","Topical natamycin and systemic voriconazole","Intravenous fluconazole and surgical debridement","Intravenous caspofungin alone","Oral itraconazole and observation"],"a":0,"e":"Rhinoorbital mucormycosis requires simultaneous liposomal amphotericin B, urgent extensive surgical debridement of all necrotic tissue, and tight glycaemic control. Delay in any component dramatically increases mortality.<br><br>Posaconazole or isavuconazole can be used as step-down therapy or in amphotericin-intolerant patients. Orbital exenteration may be required if orbital contents are involved.<br><br>Fluconazole (C) has no activity against Mucorales. Natamycin (B) is topical and inadequate. Caspofungin alone (D) is insufficient against Mucorales. Oral itraconazole (E) is completely inadequate for invasive mucormycosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 30-year-old presents with bilateral proptosis, café-au-lait spots, and bilateral optic nerve gliomas on MRI. Which gene mutation is responsible?","o":["RB1 gene on chromosome 13","WT1 gene on chromosome 11","VHL gene on chromosome 3","NF2 gene on chromosome 22","NF1 gene on chromosome 17"],"a":4,"e":"Neurofibromatosis type 1 is caused by mutations in the NF1 gene on chromosome 17q11 encoding neurofibromin, a tumour suppressor. Bilateral optic nerve gliomas combined with café-au-lait spots, axillary freckling, Lisch nodules, and neurofibromas confirm NF1.<br><br>Optic gliomas in NF1 are typically low-grade pilocytic astrocytomas with more indolent behaviour than sporadic optic gliomas. Bilateral proptosis with café-au-lait spots linking neurofibromatosis to sphenoid wing dysplasia is a classic association.<br><br>RB1 (A) causes retinoblastoma. WT1 (B) causes Wilms tumour and aniridia. VHL (C) causes haemangioblastoma and clear cell renal carcinoma. NF2 (D) causes bilateral acoustic neuromas.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 52-year-old with bilateral TED and significant inferior rectus restriction in both eyes complains of diplopia in all positions of gaze. Prisms only partially control the diplopia. What surgical option addresses the diplopia?","o":["Bilateral inferior rectus recession surgery","Bilateral orbital decompression first","Botulinum toxin injection into the superior rectus","Bilateral lateral tarsorrhaphy","Bilateral medial rectus resection"],"a":0,"e":"Bilateral inferior rectus recession is the surgical treatment for vertical diplopia caused by inferior rectus restriction in thyroid eye disease. Surgery is performed after disease inactivation and orbital decompression, as decompression may alter the strabismus pattern.<br><br>Adjustable sutures allow postoperative fine-tuning of alignment. The surgeon aims for single binocular vision in primary gaze and downgaze for reading.<br><br>Tarsorrhaphy (D) addresses exposure not diplopia. Orbital decompression (B) precedes strabismus surgery but does not directly treat diplopia. Botulinum toxin (C) temporarily weakens the superior rectus not the inferior. Medial rectus resection (E) treats horizontal not vertical diplopia.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 42-year-old presents with painless progressive unilateral proptosis. MRI shows an enhancing mass in the lacrimal gland with heterogeneous signal and T2 hypointensity. Duration of symptoms is six months. What does the rapid progression of a lacrimal gland mass suggest?","o":["Pleomorphic adenoma with pseudocapsule","Inflammatory dacryoadenitis from sarcoidosis","Dermoid cyst of the lacrimal gland fossa","IgG4-related lacrimal gland involvement","Malignant lacrimal gland tumour"],"a":4,"e":"Rapid progression of a lacrimal gland mass over less than 12 months, pain, bony erosion on CT, and T2 hypointensity on MRI indicating high cellularity all suggest malignant lacrimal gland tumour, most likely adenoid cystic carcinoma.<br><br>The one-year rule states that benign lesions such as pleomorphic adenoma grow for more than 12 months, while malignant lacrimal gland tumours typically present within 12 months of symptom onset.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (A) grows slowly over years. Sarcoidosis (B) shows bilateral lacrimal gland enlargement without bony erosion. IgG4-related disease (D) responds to steroids. Dermoid cyst (C) occurs at suture lines without lacrimal gland origin.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 25-year-old is found on MRI to have a cystic orbital lesion with a fat-fluid level and connection to the skin at the superotemporal orbital rim through the zygomaticofrontal suture. What is the most appropriate management?","o":["Complete surgical excision without capsule rupture","Observation with annual MRI","Incisional biopsy for histological confirmation","Aspiration of the cyst contents","Steroid injection into the cyst"],"a":0,"e":"Dermoid cyst must be completely excised without capsule rupture. Spillage of the cyst contents, particularly keratinous and lipid material, causes a severe granulomatous inflammatory reaction that is very difficult to treat and causes significant scarring.<br><br>Preoperative CT or MRI delineates any intracranial component through the suture requiring combined neurosurgical approach for dumbbell-shaped dermoids.<br><br>Aspiration (D) risks rupture and inflammation. Observation (B) is inappropriate for a growing dermoid. Incisional biopsy (C) violates the capsule causing the same granulomatous complication. Steroid injection (E) does not treat the cyst.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old man presents with unilateral proptosis, periorbital bruising, and enophthalmos following a blunt injury to the orbit. CT shows a blowout fracture of the orbital floor with prolapse of orbital fat into the maxillary sinus. When should surgical repair be performed?","o":["Immediately within 24 hours always","After three months of observation","Never, as blowout fractures heal spontaneously","Only if diplopia persists after six months","Within two weeks, earlier if muscle entrapment causes ischaemia"],"a":4,"e":"Orbital floor blowout fractures require surgical repair within two weeks to prevent permanent fibrosis and diplopia. Urgent repair within 24 to 48 hours is indicated when the oculocardiac reflex causes bradycardia and nausea or when CT shows white-eyed blowout in children suggesting trapdoor fracture with muscle ischaemia.<br><br>The oculocardiac reflex from muscle entrapment in children constitutes a surgical emergency.<br><br>Immediate repair always (A) is incorrect as most cases are managed within two weeks. Three months of observation (B) risks permanent fibrosis. Spontaneous healing (C) is incorrect. Six months of diplopia (D) is too long.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with right proptosis, chemosis, and elevated IOP of 32 mmHg. He had a right orbital fracture repair six months ago with a titanium mesh implant. What is the most likely cause of his current presentation?","o":["Orbital pseudotumour from foreign body reaction","Titanium mesh infection causing orbital cellulitis","Thyroid eye disease unrelated to prior surgery","Recurrent orbital floor fracture","Delayed haemorrhage from the titanium mesh"],"a":0,"e":"Titanium implants can rarely provoke a foreign body granulomatous reaction in the orbit causing delayed proptosis, chemosis, and raised IOP months to years after implantation. CT shows soft tissue around the mesh without abscess formation.<br><br>Management includes systemic steroids and implant removal if no response to steroids. PEEK or porous polyethylene implants have lower rates of foreign body reaction.<br><br>Recurrent fracture (D) would be visible on CT. Titanium infection (B) causes fever and acute onset. Thyroid eye disease (C) is bilateral. Delayed haemorrhage (E) causes acute painful proptosis not subacute presentation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old presents with progressive bilateral proptosis and diabetes insipidus. MRI shows infundibular thickening and bilateral orbital masses. Biopsy shows CD1a-positive histiocytes with Birbeck granules. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Langerhans cell histiocytosis with orbital and pituitary involvement","Erdheim-Chester disease","IgG4-related orbital and pituitary disease","Sarcoidosis with pituitary involvement","Orbital lymphoma with central nervous system involvement"],"a":0,"e":"Multisystem Langerhans cell histiocytosis causes orbital bone lesions, diabetes insipidus from pituitary stalk involvement, and skin lesions. CD1a positivity and Birbeck granules on electron microscopy confirm the Langerhans cell origin.<br><br>Chemotherapy with vinblastine and prednisolone is used for multisystem disease. Diabetes insipidus may be permanent despite treatment of the systemic disease.<br><br>Sarcoidosis (D) shows non-caseating granulomas not CD1a-positive histiocytes. Erdheim-Chester disease (B) shows foamy histiocytes without Birbeck granules. IgG4-related disease (C) shows IgG4-positive plasma cells. Orbital lymphoma (E) shows CD20-positive B-cells.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 38-year-old woman with TED has inactive disease and is counselled about smoking. What specific advice should be given regarding smoking and TED?","o":["Smoking is only harmful during the active phase and safe afterwards","Passive smoking has no effect on TED outcomes","Smoking cessation after TED onset does not improve prognosis","Moderate smoking of less than ten cigarettes daily is safe in TED","Smoking increases TED risk fourfold and impairs response to immunosuppressive treatment"],"a":4,"e":"Smoking is the single most important modifiable risk factor for TED, increasing risk fourfold. Active smokers respond significantly worse to intravenous methylprednisolone and orbital radiotherapy. Even passive smoking impairs outcomes.<br><br>Cessation at any stage improves prognosis and response to treatment. Patients must be strongly counselled that smoking cessation is as important as any medical treatment for TED.<br><br>Smoking only harmful during active phase (A) is incorrect. Passive smoking (B) does impair outcomes. Cessation after onset (C) does improve prognosis. Ten cigarettes daily (D) is not safe; even low-level smoking impairs TED outcomes.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 60-year-old presents with left proptosis and periorbital fullness. CT shows a well-defined left retrobulbar mass with calcification. No bony destruction. He is asymptomatic with 6/6 vision. What is the most appropriate management?","o":["Observation with serial MRI and visual monitoring","Intravenous antibiotics empirically","Systemic corticosteroids for orbital pseudotumour","Immediate surgical excision via lateral orbitotomy","Orbital radiotherapy immediately"],"a":0,"e":"An asymptomatic well-defined calcified orbital mass with no bony destruction and 6/6 vision in an older patient can be managed by watchful waiting with serial imaging. Calcification suggests a benign lesion such as cavernous haemangioma with phlebolith or long-standing orbital tumour.<br><br>Surgery carries risks. Intervention is reserved for lesions showing growth, threatening vision, or causing significant proptosis. Biopsy may be considered if the diagnosis is uncertain.<br><br>Immediate excision (D) is not indicated for an asymptomatic lesion. Antibiotics (B) are irrelevant. Corticosteroids (C) are for orbital pseudotumour which is painful. Orbital radiotherapy (E) is for lymphoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 7-year-old girl presents with acute proptosis, restricted eye movement, and periorbital swelling after minor trauma. CT shows a small orbital floor fracture with inferior rectus entrapped in the fracture site and bradycardia. What is the most appropriate management?","o":["Observation for two weeks then surgical review","Intravenous antibiotics and observation","Botulinum toxin to the inferior rectus","Systemic steroids to reduce periorbital swelling","Immediate surgical release of the entrapped muscle"],"a":4,"e":"Paediatric white-eyed blowout fracture with muscle entrapment causes the oculocardiac reflex producing bradycardia, nausea, and vomiting. This constitutes a surgical emergency requiring immediate release of the entrapped inferior rectus to prevent ischaemic muscle necrosis and permanent diplopia.<br><br>Unlike adults where surgery can wait two weeks, children with trapdoor fractures and muscle entrapment require same-day surgical repair to preserve muscle viability. Acute proptosis with motility restriction in a child after minor trauma should always raise orbital haemorrhage.<br><br>Observation for two weeks (A) causes permanent ischaemic muscle damage. Antibiotics (B) treat infection not entrapment. Systemic steroids (D) do not release the entrapped muscle. Botulinum toxin (C) has no role in acute muscle entrapment.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 65-year-old presents with bilateral proptosis that has gradually resolved over two years without treatment. He has bilateral mild dry eyes. What condition can cause spontaneous regression of bilateral proptosis?","o":["Bilateral orbital lymphoma","Bilateral thyroid eye disease entering inactive phase","IgG4-related orbital disease after spontaneous remission","Bilateral orbital pseudotumour resolving spontaneously","Bilateral orbital varix thrombosing spontaneously"],"a":1,"e":"Thyroid eye disease naturally follows an active inflammatory phase lasting six months to two years followed by a stable inactive phase where inflammation subsides and some proptosis may reduce spontaneously. Dry eyes persist from lacrimal gland fibrosis.<br><br>Understanding the natural history prevents unnecessary treatment during the spontaneous resolution phase. Surgical rehabilitation is planned after at least six months of disease stability.<br><br>Bilateral orbital lymphoma (A) does not resolve spontaneously. IgG4-related disease (C) rarely resolves without treatment. Bilateral pseudotumour (D) requires steroids for resolution. Bilateral varix thrombosis (E) would cause sudden painful changes not gradual resolution.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old presents with proptosis and choroidal striae on fundoscopy. There is no disc swelling or RAPD. CT shows a posterior orbital mass indenting the globe. What investigation best demonstrates the choroidal striae?","o":["Fluorescein angiography","OCT of the optic disc","Indocyanine green angiography","B-scan ultrasonography","Visual evoked potentials"],"a":0,"e":"Choroidal striae from orbital mass compression of the posterior globe are best demonstrated by fluorescein angiography showing alternating hyperfluorescent and hypofluorescent lines corresponding to the folds in the choroid. They are also visible on fundoscopy and OCT of the posterior pole.<br><br>Choroidal striae in the absence of disc swelling and RAPD suggest compressive mass without optic nerve compromise. Surgical planning depends on the nature of the orbital mass.<br><br>OCT of the optic disc (B) assesses the nerve fibre layer. ICG angiography (C) assesses choroidal circulation but FA shows striae better. B-scan (D) identifies the mass but not the striae pattern. VEPs (E) assess optic nerve function not choroidal anatomy.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 20-year-old man presents with progressive right proptosis over six months. MRI shows a fusiform right optic nerve mass with kinking and buckling of the nerve. He has no café-au-lait spots or family history of NF1. What is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","o":["Sporadic optic nerve glioma","Optic nerve sheath meningioma","NF1-associated optic nerve glioma","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Orbital pseudotumour myositic type"],"a":0,"e":"Sporadic optic nerve glioma without NF1 features presents in older children and young adults and has a more aggressive behaviour than NF1-associated gliomas. They are more likely to require treatment with chemotherapy or radiotherapy and carry a worse visual prognosis.<br><br>MRI distinguishes glioma from meningioma by the pattern of optic nerve enlargement. Glioma causes fusiform nerve expansion while meningioma shows tram-track enhancement with central nerve sparing.<br><br>NF1-associated glioma (C) requires NF1 features. Optic nerve sheath meningioma (B) shows tram-track enhancement. Cavernous haemangioma (D) is intraconal not along the nerve. Orbital pseudotumour myositic type (E) involves the extraocular muscles not the optic nerve.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 10-year-old presents with bilateral exophthalmos and a high forehead. CT shows bilateral shallow orbits from premature synostosis of the coronal sutures. What is the syndrome?","o":["Crouzon syndrome","Treacher Collins syndrome","Goldenhar syndrome","Apert syndrome","Pierre Robin sequence"],"a":0,"e":"Crouzon syndrome is caused by FGFR2 mutations causing premature fusion of the coronal and sagittal sutures producing a shallow orbit with bilateral proptosis and midface hypoplasia. The facies is characteristic with exophthalmos, hypertelorism, and midface retrusion.<br><br>Orbital decompression and fronto-orbital advancement surgery correct the proptosis and improve the orbital volume. Regular ophthalmological surveillance detects exposure keratopathy and optic nerve compression.<br><br>Apert syndrome (D) combines craniosynostosis with syndactyly. Treacher Collins (B) causes malar and mandibular hypoplasia without proptosis. Goldenhar (C) causes hemifacial microsomia. Pierre Robin (E) causes micrognathia and cleft palate.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old woman presents with exophthalmos and is found on CT to have bilateral retrobulbar fat expansion without extraocular muscle enlargement. TRAb is positive. What specific pathological process causes fat expansion in thyroid eye disease?","o":["Orbital venous congestion causing fat oedema","Orbital fibroblast stimulation by TRAb causing glycosaminoglycan and adipogenesis expansion","Inflammatory oedema from lymphocyte infiltration of fat","Mechanical obstruction of lymphatic drainage causing fat swelling","Thyroid hormone directly stimulating orbital fat synthesis"],"a":1,"e":"TRAb cross-reacts with IGF-1 receptors on orbital fibroblasts stimulating glycosaminoglycan hyaluronan production and adipogenesis. This expands the orbital fat volume causing proptosis even without significant extraocular muscle enlargement in the fat-predominant subtype of TED.<br><br>Teprotumumab specifically blocks the IGF-1 receptor reducing both the fat and muscle components of TED orbital expansion.<br><br>Venous congestion (A) causes transient oedema not permanent expansion. Lymphocyte infiltration (C) is correct but incomplete; orbital fibroblast stimulation is the primary mechanism. Lymphatic obstruction (D) is not the mechanism. Thyroid hormone directly (E) is not the primary mechanism.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 48-year-old presents with right proptosis and episodic ipsilateral headache. MRI shows a well-defined oval mass in the right orbital apex. He has a history of a posterior communicating artery aneurysm clipped six years ago. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital pseudotumour","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Recurrent aneurysm extending into the orbit","Orbital meningioma","Orbital lymphoma"],"a":1,"e":"Cavernous haemangioma is the most common benign intraconal orbital tumour in adults. A well-defined oval mass at the orbital apex with episodic headache from pressure effects and a history of prior aneurysm is coincidental. The MRI characteristics of T2 hyperintensity and progressive enhancement confirm cavernous haemangioma.<br><br>Surgical excision via lateral orbitotomy or endoscopic orbital approach removes the tumour completely. Orbital apex location requires careful surgical planning.<br><br>Orbital pseudotumour (A) is painful without encapsulation. Recurrent aneurysm (C) would show on CT angiography. Orbital meningioma (D) shows tram-track enhancement. Orbital lymphoma (E) is moulded and extraconal.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 6-year-old presents with fever, periorbital swelling, and limited motility. A CT shows a medial subperiosteal abscess. He is started on intravenous co-amoxiclav. After 48 hours there is no improvement. What is the next step?","o":["Surgical drainage of the subperiosteal abscess","Switch to oral antibiotics","Add topical antibiotic eye drops","Add oral metronidazole","Lumbar puncture to exclude meningitis"],"a":0,"e":"Failure to improve within 48 hours of appropriate intravenous antibiotics in orbital cellulitis with subperiosteal abscess requires urgent surgical drainage. Medial subperiosteal abscesses are drained endoscopically via a transnasal route or open medial orbitotomy.<br><br>Indications for immediate surgery include vision loss, RAPD, bilateral signs suggesting cavernous sinus thrombosis, failure of 48 hours of antibiotics, or abscess larger than 10 mm.<br><br>Adding oral metronidazole (D) without surgery is insufficient. Switching to oral antibiotics (B) is inappropriate for a worsening case. Topical drops (C) have no role. Lumbar puncture (E) is considered if meningism is present but does not treat the abscess.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 50-year-old presents with bilateral retraction of the upper eyelid. She is euthyroid with normal TFTs. Both eyes show 3 mm of superior scleral show. What is the most likely cause of bilateral lid retraction in a euthyroid patient?","o":["Dorsal midbrain syndrome causing lid retraction","Bilateral Horner syndrome","Bilateral myasthenia gravis causing lid retraction","Bilateral facial palsy causing lid retraction","Bilateral Marcus Gunn jaw-winking ptosis"],"a":0,"e":"Collier sign is bilateral upper lid retraction from dorsal midbrain compression of the pretectal inhibitory pathway to the levator causing disinhibited lid elevation. It is a component of Parinaud syndrome along with upgaze palsy and convergence retraction nystagmus.<br><br>Hydrocephalus and pineal region tumours are the most common causes. Neuroimaging is mandatory in any patient with unexplained bilateral lid retraction without thyroid disease.<br><br>Bilateral facial palsy (D) causes inability to close the lids not retraction. Horner syndrome (B) causes ptosis. Myasthenia gravis (C) causes ptosis not retraction. Marcus Gunn (E) is unilateral congenital ptosis with synkinesis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 45-year-old presents with a left orbital mass. Biopsy shows a benign spindle cell tumour with S100 positivity and Antoni A and Antoni B areas. What is the diagnosis?","o":["Orbital fibrous histiocytoma","Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma","Orbital cavernous haemangioma","Orbital lymphoma","Schwannoma of the orbit"],"a":4,"e":"Orbital schwannoma is a benign peripheral nerve sheath tumour showing S100 positivity, Antoni A areas with compact spindle cells in palisades, and Antoni B areas with loosely arranged myxoid stroma. It arises from peripheral nerves in the orbit.<br><br>Complete surgical excision is curative. Schwannomas have a pseudocapsule allowing clean dissection. Recurrence after complete excision is uncommon. Association with NF2 should be considered in bilateral cases. Antoni A and B areas with Verocay bodies on biopsy are the defining histological signature of a schwannoma.<br><br>Fibrous histiocytoma (A) is S100-negative. Rhabdomyosarcoma (B) shows cross-striations. Cavernous haemangioma (C) shows vascular spaces. Orbital lymphoma (D) shows lymphoid infiltrate without Antoni areas.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 55-year-old presents with bilateral proptosis, periorbital oedema, and elevated serum IgG4. MRI shows bilateral lacrimal gland masses, infraorbital nerve thickening, and bilateral orbital fat enhancement. Biopsy shows storiform fibrosis with IgG4-positive plasma cells exceeding 50 per high power field. What is the diagnosis and first-line treatment?","o":["Orbital pseudotumour treated with orbital radiotherapy","Orbital lymphoma treated with chemotherapy","Sarcoidosis treated with systemic steroids","Sjögren syndrome treated with hydroxychloroquine","IgG4-related orbital disease treated with systemic corticosteroids"],"a":4,"e":"IgG4-related orbital disease requires IgG4 serum elevation and histology showing storiform fibrosis with more than 10 IgG4-positive plasma cells per high power field. Systemic corticosteroids achieve excellent initial response in most patients.<br><br>Rituximab depletes B-cells and is effective for steroid-dependent or refractory cases. Multisystem involvement of pancreas, kidneys, and salivary glands requires multidisciplinary management alongside ophthalmological treatment.<br><br>Orbital pseudotumour (A) lacks IgG4 histology. Orbital lymphoma (B) shows CD20-positive B-cell infiltrate. Sarcoidosis (C) shows non-caseating granulomas. Sjögren syndrome (D) has anti-SS-A antibodies and different histology.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
];